ground:honeyDew;\"|2.4% ''222''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1916 United States presidential election|1916]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|37.3% ''1,947''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''56.0%''' ''2,928''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|6.7% ''351''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1912 United States presidential election|1912]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|16.0% ''812''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''54.2%''' ''2,760''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|29.9% ''1,520''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1908 United States presidential election|1908]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|35.9% ''2,185''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''55.0%''' ''3,345''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|9.1% ''553''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1904 United States presidential election|1904]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|40.7% ''2,565''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''49.7%''' ''3,127''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|9.6% ''604''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1900 United States presidential election|1900]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|37.5% ''2,290''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''58.9%''' ''3,599''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|3.6% ''217''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1896 United States presidential election|1896]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|36.6% ''2,212''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''61.7%''' ''3,728''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|1.6% ''98''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1892 United States presidential election|1892]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|33.9% ''1,668''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''55.4%''' ''2,725''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|10.7% ''528''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1888 United States presidential election|1888]]'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|37.2% ''1,926''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''56.8%''' ''2,942''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|6.1% ''314''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1840= 1822\n|1850= 6152\n|1860= 10844\n|1870= 13585\n|1880= 18442\n|1890= 21514\n|1900= 23449\n|1910= 22418\n|1920= 20509\n|1930= 18411\n|1940= 19099\n|1950= 19564\n|1960= 21220\n|1970= 23821\n|1980= 25401\n|1990= 25948\n|2000= 27600\n|2010= 27636\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=28206\n|estref=\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/in190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2013<ref name=\"census-quickfacts\"/> 2018<ref name=2018pop>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/quickfacts/fact/table/wellscountyindiana/PST045218 |title=QuickFacts. Wells County, Indiana. |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=July 26, 2019 }}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[2010 United States Census]], there were 27,636&nbsp;people, 10,780&nbsp;households, and 7,684&nbsp;families residing in the county.<ref name=\"census-dp1\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US18179\n  |title=DP-1 Profile of General Population and Housing Characteristics: 2010 Demographic Profile Data\n  |accessdate=2015-07-10\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213020926/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/DPDP1/0500000US18179\n  |archive-date=2020-02-13\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref> The population density was {{convert|75.1|PD/sqmi}}. There were 11,659 housing units at an average density of {{convert|31.7|/sqmi}}.<ref name=\"census-density\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US18179\n  |accessdate=2015-07-10\n  |title=Population, Housing Units, Area, and Density: 2010 - County\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212204438/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_SF1/GCTPH1.CY10/0500000US18179\n  |archive-date=2020-02-12\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref> The racial makeup of the county was 97.3% white, 0.4% Asian, 0.3% American Indian, 0.3% black or African American, 0.8% from other races, and 0.9% from two or more races. Those of Hispanic or Latino origin made up 2.0% of the population.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/> In terms of ancestry, 38.4% were [[Germans|German]], 12.3% were [[English people|English]], 10.8% were [[Irish people|Irish]], and 10.3% were [[Americans|American]].<ref name=\"census-dp2\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0400000US18%7c0500000US18179\n  |title=DP02 SELECTED SOCIAL CHARACTERISTICS IN THE UNITED STATES \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates\n  |accessdate=2015-07-10\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200214002503/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP02/0400000US18%7C0500000US18179\n  |archive-date=2020-02-14\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\nOf the 10,780&nbsp;households, 33.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 58.1% were married couples living together, 8.6% had a female householder with no husband present, 28.7% were non-families, and 24.8% of all households were made up of individuals. The average household size was 2.52 and the average family size was 3.00. The median age was 40.2 years.<ref name=\"census-dp1\"/>\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $47,697 and the median income for a family was $56,885. Males had a median income of $41,871 versus $30,031 for females. The per capita income for the county was $23,169. About 6.2% of families and 8.0% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 10.8% of those under age 18 and 3.6% of those age 65 or over.<ref name=\"census-dp3\">{{cite web\n  |url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0400000US18%7c0500000US18179\n  |title=DP03 SELECTED ECONOMIC CHARACTERISTICS \u2013 2006-2010 American Community Survey 5-Year Estimates\n  |accessdate=2015-07-10\n  |publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]\n  |archive-url=https://archive.today/20200214002931/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/10_5YR/DP03/0400000US18%7C0500000US18179\n  |archive-date=2020-02-14\n  |url-status=dead\n  }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Wells County, Indiana]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ohiohistorycentral.org/entry.php?rec=403 William Wells]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n<!--added under references heading by script-assisted edit-->\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Wells County, Indiana\n|North     = [[Allen County, Indiana|Allen County]]\n|Northeast = \n|East      = [[Adams County, Indiana|Adams County]]\n|Southeast = [[Jay County, Indiana|Jay County]]\n|South     = [[Blackford County, Indiana|Blackford County]]\n|Southwest = \n|West      = [[Grant County, Indiana|Grant County]]\n|Northwest = [[Huntington County, Indiana|Huntington County]]\n}}\n{{Wells County, Indiana}}\n{{Fort Wayne Metro}}\n{{Indiana}}\n\n{{coord|40.73|-85.22|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-IN_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Wells County, Indiana| ]]\n[[Category:Indiana counties]]\n[[Category:1837 establishments in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1837]]\n[[Category:Fort Wayne, IN Metropolitan Statistical Area]]\n", "name_user": "Whoisjohngalt", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wells_County,_Indiana"}
{"title_page": "High Expectations", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 studio album by Mabel}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = High Expectations\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Mabel (singer)|Mabel]]\n| cover        = Mabel - High Expectations.png\n| alt          = Colour photograph of Mabel\n| caption      = \n| released     = {{Start date|df=yes|2019|08|02}}\n| recorded     = \n| studio       = {{hlist|Rokstone, London|Spaceship, London and Los Angeles|The Collection, London|Breakfast, [[Kensal Town|Kensal Rise]]|[[Sarm West Studios|SARM Music Village]], [[Ladbroke Grove]]}}\n| genre        = *[[Pop music|Pop]]<ref name=\"Skinny\"/>\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]<ref name=\"Guardian\" />\n| length       = 61:22\n| label        = {{hlist|[[Polydor Records|Polydor]]|[[Capitol Records|Capitol]]}}\n| producer     = {{hlist|[[Steve Mac]]|[[Fraser T. Smith]]|[[Jordan Riley]]|[[Tre Jean-Marie]]|[[Dre Skull]]|[[Pop & Oak|Oak]]|[[Al Shux]]|MakeYouKnowLove|169|[[Snakehips (duo)|Snakehips]]|[[MXXWLL]]|[[MNEK]]|[[Stephen Kozmeniuk|Koz]]}}\n| prev_title   = [[Ivy to Roses]]\n| prev_year    = 2017\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{Singles\n | name        = High Expectations\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Don't Call Me Up]]\n | single1date = 18 January 2019\n | single2     = [[Mad Love (Mabel song)|Mad Love]]\n | single2date = 7 June 2019\n | single3     = [[OK (Anxiety Anthem)]]\n | single3date = 2 August 2019<ref name = \"Dazed\"/>\n | single4     = [[God Is a Dancer]]\n | single4date = 20 September 2019\n | single5     = [[Boyfriend (Mabel song)|Boyfriend]]\n | single5date = 26 February 2020\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''High Expectations''''' is the debut studio album by English singer and songwriter [[Mabel (singer)|Mabel]], released on 2 August 2019 internationally by  [[Polydor Records]] and in the United States by [[Capitol Records]] and [[Universal Music Group|Universal]]. Mabel worked with writers and producers such as [[Tre Jean-Marie]], [[Steve Mac]] and [[MNEK]] to create the record, with its music incorporating genres of [[Pop music|pop]] and [[R&B]].\n\nTwo singles and one promotional single were released from the album. Its lead single, \"[[Don't Call Me Up]]\", was released in January 2019 and was a commercial success, reaching the top ten in several countries and receiving a platinum certification in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/news/mabel-is-moving-on-with-new-pop-banger-dont-call-me-up|title=Mabel Is Moving On With New Pop Banger 'Don't Call Me Up'|website=Clash Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-official-top-40-biggest-singles-of-2019-so-far__25951/|title=The Top 40 biggest singles of 2019 so far|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en|access-date=2019-05-12}}</ref> The song peaked at number three on the [[UK Singles Chart]], becoming Mabel's highest charting single and her second top 10 single. \"[[Mad Love (Mabel song)|Mad Love]]\" was released as the second single from the album, and also performed well on charts internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/mabel/status/1135958107547492352?s=21|title=MY NEW SINGLE MAD LOVE DROPPING THIS FRIDAY!!! Make sure u pre-save!! Can\u2019t wait for you to hear it|last=Mabel|date=2019-06-04|website=Twitter|language=en|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref> The song peaked at number eight in the United Kingdom, becoming her third top 10 single. A promotional single, \"Bad Behaviour\", was released with an accompanying music video on 23 July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8523575/mabel-bad-behaviour-song-tour-dates|title=Mabel Releases Sultry Song 'Bad Behaviour,' Announces Tour: Listen|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> In order to promote the album, Mabel announced the High Expectations Tour, consisting of 24 shows in Europe and commencing in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguideliverpool.com/mabel-announces-high-expectations-headline-tour/|title=Mabel announces 'High Expectations' headline tour|date=19 July 2019|website=The Guide Liverpool|access-date=14 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nUpon its release, ''High Expectations'' received generally positive reviews from music critics, many of whom complimented its production and the singer's vocals. The album was also a success commercially, debuting at number three on the [[UK Albums Chart]] and at number five on the [[Irish Albums Chart]].\n\n==Background==\nIn October 2017, Mabel released her debut [[mixtape]], ''[[Ivy to Roses]]''. Its lead single, \"[[Finders Keepers (Mabel song)|Finders Keepers]]\", peaked at number eight on the UK Singles Chart and became her first top ten single. The mixtape was then reissued in January 2019, with six singles released subsequent to the original release featuring, as well as its next single \"Don't Call Me Up\". Her debut album, ''High Expectations,'' was announced on 18 April of the same year, with a scheduled release date of 12 July. The release date was later moved to 2 August.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/04/18/mabel-high-expectations-release-date|title=Mabel announces debut album High Expectations|website=The FADER|language=en|access-date=2019-08-14}}</ref>\n\n==Singles==\nThe album's first single, \"[[Don't Call Me Up]]\", was released on 18 January 2019.<ref name=\"Amazon\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Dont-Call-Me-Up/dp/B07MQ9PZQB|title=Don't Call Me Up|publisher=[[Amazon (company)|Amazon.com]]|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/mabel-interview-neneh-cherrys-daughter-on-her-high-expectations-and-her-battle-with-anxiety-mkschqj39|title=Mabel interview: Neneh Cherry's daughter on her High Expectations \u2014 and her battle with anxiety|last=Verrico|first=Lisa|website=[[The Sunday Times]]|date=14 July 2019|accessdate=20 August 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref> It was initially included on the 2019 reissue of ''Ivy to Roses''.<ref name=\"Amazon\"/> The song peaked at number three on the [[UK Singles Chart]] for three consecutive weeks, making it Mabel's highest charting single in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/the-official-top-40-biggest-singles-of-2019-so-far__25951/|title=The Official Top 40 biggest singles of 2019 so far|last=Copsey|first=Rob|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=2 April 2019|accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicweek.com/analysis/read/charts-analysis-ariana-grande-scores-easy-second-week-at-summer/075179|title=Charts analysis: Ariana Grande scores easy second week at summit|last=Jones|first=Alan|website=[[Music Week]]|date=1 February 2019|accessdate=5 April 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref> It became her international mainstream breakthrough, charting in the top 10 in over 20 other countries including Belgium, Ireland, the Netherlands and Norway where it reached the top three.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ultratop.be/nl/song/1c0232/Mabel-[UK]-Don't-Call-Me-Up|title=Mabel [UK] - Don't Call Me Up|language=Dutch|website=[[Ultratop]]|accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Ireland\">{{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Mabel+%5BUK%5D|title=Discography Mabel [UK]|website=Irishcharts.com|accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref> The track also became the singer's first US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart entry where it rose to number 66.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8505326/mabel-scores-first-billboard-hot-100-hit-dont-call-me-up|title=Mabel Scores First Billboard Hot 100 Hit With 'Don't Call Me Up'|last=Zellner|first=Xander|website=Billboard|date=2 April 2019|accessdate=5 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/Mabel/chart-history/hot-100|title=Mabel Chart History|website=Billboard|accessdate=20 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Mad Love (Mabel song)|Mad Love]]\" was released as the second single on 7 June 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3126729/mabel-mad-love-video/|title=Mabel Dares You to Give Her 'Mad Love' in Eye-popping New Video|last=Roth|first=Madeline|website=[[MTV News]]|date=7 June 2019|accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref> It became Mabel's third UK top-10 single, peaking at number eight,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicweek.com/analysis/read/charts-analysis-ed-sheeran-dominates-singles-top-10/076718|title=Charts analysis: Ed Sheeran dominates singles Top 10|last=Jones|first=Alan|website=Music Week|date=5 July 2019|accessdate=6 August 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref> and her second top-10 single in Ireland where it reached number six.<ref name=\"Ireland\"/> \n\n\"[[OK (Anxiety Anthem)]]\" was positioned as the album's third single, being released alongside the album.<ref name=\"Dazed\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/beauty/soul/article/45659/1/exclusive-premiere-mabels-mental-health-tackling-ok-anxiety-anthem-music-video|title=PREMIERE: MABEL'S MENTAL HEALTH-TACKLING \u2018OK, ANXIETY ANTHEM\u2019 MUSIC VIDEO|last=Peters|first=Alex|date=2019-08-16|website=Dazed Beauty|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> The song received a music video, directed by Jade Jackman which premiered on ''[[Dazed]]'' on 16 August 2019.<ref name=\"Dazed\" />\n\n\"[[God Is a Dancer]]\" with [[Ti\u00ebsto|Tiesto]] and \"[[Boyfriend (Mabel song)|Boyfriend]]\" are both featured on the iTunes special edition of the album, therefore serving as the fourth and fifth singles of the album.\n\n=== Promotional singles ===\nThe album's first promotional single, \"Bad Behaviour\", was released on 23 July 2019 along with a music video directed by Oliver Kane.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7837460/mabel-embraces-party-vibes-on-new-track-bad-behaviour|title=Mabel Embraces Party Vibes On New Track 'Bad Behaviour'|last=Nied|first=Mike|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|date=23 July 2019|accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://video-streaming.orange.fr/musique/mabel-bad-behaviour-CNT000001hpZVD.html|title=Mabel - Bad Behaviour|website=[[Orange S.A.]]|accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref> The track debuted at number 94 on the UK Singles Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/52386/mabel/|title=Mabel|publisher=Official Charts Company|accessdate=21 August 2019}} </ref> \n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 61/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/high-expectations/mabel|title=High Expectations by Mabel Critic Reviews and Tracks|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref>\n| rev1 = ''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]''\n| rev1Score = 7/10<ref name=\"Clash\">{{cite web|url=https://clashmusic.com/reviews/mabel-high-expectations|title=Mabel - High Expectations|last=Hale|first=Joe|website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|date=14 August 2019|accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"DIY\">{{cite web|url=http://diymag.com/2019/08/02/mabel-high-expectations-album-review|title=Mabel - High Expectations|last=Taylor|first=Chris|website=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]|date=2 August 2019|accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> \n| rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]'' \n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/aug/01/mabel-high-expectations-review|title=Mabel: High Expectations review \u2013 confident pop lacks personality|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|author-link=Alexis Petridis|website=[[The Guardian]]|date=1 August 2019|accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[musicOMH]]'' \n| rev4Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"musicOMH\">{{cite web |url=https://www.musicomh.com/reviews/albums/mabel-high-expectations|title=Mabel \u2013 High Expectations|last=Devlin|first=Ben |website=[[musicOMH]]|date=5 August 2019|accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref> \n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"NME\" >{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/mabel-high-expectations-album-review#FJXYBYSLMyQQCVVv.99|title=Mabel \u2013 'High Expectations' review|last=Mylrea|first=Hannah|website=[[NME]]|date=2 August 2019|accessdate=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[The Observer]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"The Observer\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/aug/03/mabel-high-expectations-album-review|title=Mabel: High Expectations review \u2013 something sassy this way comes|last=Empire|first=Kitty|author-link=Kitty Empire|website=[[The Observer]]|date=3 August 2019|accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|5|10}}<ref name=\"PopMatters\">{{cite web|url=https://www.popmatters.com/mabel-high-expectations-review-2639808560.html|title=Mabel: High Expectations (album review)|last=Jacobs|first=Mick|website=[[PopMatters]]|date=14 August 2019|accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Q magazine\">{{cite magazine|title=Q Review New Albums: Mabel - High Expectations|last=Barton|first=Laura|magazine=[[Q (magazine)|Q]]|page=112|date=September 2019|issn=0955-4955}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[The Skinny (magazine)|The Skinny]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"Skinny\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theskinny.co.uk/music/reviews/albums/mabel-high-expectations |title=Mabel album review: High Expectations|last=Wright|first=Andrew|website=[[The Skinny (magazine)|The Skinny]]|date=2 August 2019|accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev10Score = 6/10<ref name=\"Uncut\">{{cite magazine|title=New Albums: Mabel - High Expectations|last=Sharp|first=Johnny|magazine=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]|page=29|date=September 2019|issn=1368-0722}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''High Expectations'' received generally positive reviews from music critics. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalised]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an [[weighted mean|average]] score of 61, based on 10 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/> Reviewing the album for ''[[musicOMH]]'', Ben Devlin hailed it as \"a convincing display of versatility and quality songwriting that firmly establishes Mabel as a force to be reckoned with in UK pop\",<ref name=\"musicOMH\"/> while Chris Taylor of ''[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]'' regarded it as \"effortlessly cool\" with \"no faux-earnestness\".<ref name=\"DIY\"/> ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine's Laura Barton called the album \"highly polished\" and said the singer \"perfected the art of writing songs that even on first listen sound totally ubiquitous\".<ref name=\"Q magazine\"/> In ''[[NME]]'', Hannah Mylrea wrote that Mabel's \"gorgeous silky vocals soar, the glossy production is stellar, but the exuberance and effervescent attitude that make tunes like 'Don't Call Me Up' so brilliant aren't found throughout.\"<ref name=\"NME\"/>\n\nAndrew Wright of ''[[The Skinny (magazine)|The Skinny]]'' argued that the singer found her individual identity with ''High Expectations'' which he described as well-rounded despite \"some over-zealous Top 40 attempts\".<ref name=\"Skinny\"/> Conversely, Joe Hale of ''[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]'' found it \"almost too airbrushed, with Mabel playing it a little too safe to qualify being described as wholly original or progressive\", but concluded that it had \"some real highlights\" and \"moments of talent and flair\".<ref name=\"Clash\"/> Despite finding the album strong and well-crafted, ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s [[Alexis Petridis]] also believed it lacked personality and only \"occasionally hints its maker might be more interesting and individual\".<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> [[Kitty Empire]] was more critical in ''[[The Observer]]'', writing, \"''High Expectations'' is just disappointingly all right, lacking any playfulness, or top spin, or a sense of who Mabel is,\"<ref name=\"The Observer\"/> while ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' critic Johnny Sharp commented, \"Despite some pleasant enough tunes, she lacks the vocal charisma to stand out from other wannabe [[Rihanna]]<nowiki/>s, [[Miley Cyrus|Miley]]<nowiki/>s and [[Dua Lipa]]<nowiki/>s.\"<ref name=\"Uncut\"/> Mick Jacobs of ''[[PopMatters]]'' concluded, \"Though sung in a beautiful, agile voice, the album's contents lack any innovation that truly set them apart, even amongst themselves.\"<ref name=\"PopMatters\"/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\n''High Expectations'' debuted at number three on the [[Official Albums Chart|UK Albums Chart]], behind [[Ed Sheeran]]'s ''[[No.6 Collaborations Project]]'' and [[Lewis Capaldi]]'s ''[[Divinely Uninspired to a Hellish Extent]]'', with first-week sales of 9,761 [[album-equivalent unit]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicweek.com/analysis/read/charts-analysis-no-6-at-no-1-again-for-ed-sheeran/077051|title=Charts analysis: No.6 at No.1 again for Ed Sheeran|last=Jones|first=Alan|website=Music Week|date=9 August 2019|accessdate=21 August 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref> It dropped to number 10 in its second week with sales of 4,184 units.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicweek.com/analysis/read/charts-analysis-slipknot-back-at-no-1-after-18-years/077122|title=Charts analysis: Slipknot back at No.1 after 18 years|last=Jones|first=Alan|website=Music Week|date=16 August 2019|accessdate=21 August 2019|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On the [[Irish Albums Chart]], it bowed at number five, the highest new entry for the chart dated 9 August 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/mabel-claims-the-highest-new-entry-on-the-official-irish-albums-chart-with-high-expectations__27042/|title=Mabel claims the highest new entry on the Official Irish Albums Chart with High Expectations|last=White|first=Jack|website=Official Charts Company|date=9 August 2019|accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref> The album also debuted in the top 40 in Norway and Switzerland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://norwegiancharts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Mabel+%5BUK%5D&titel=High+Expectations&cat=a|title=Mabel [UK] - High Expectations|website=Norwegiancharts.com|accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Switzerland\"/> In the US, ''High Expectations'' entered at number 198 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref name=\"US\"/> Hugh McIntyre of ''[[Forbes]]'' cited its debut as \"a prime example of how the UK and the US music industries can be drastically different\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/hughmcintyre/2019/08/16/bts-drake-tool-and-tyler-childers-5-noteworthy-moves-on-this-weeks-billboard-200/#34b34f431e4d|title=BTS, Drake, Tool And Tyler Childers: 5 Noteworthy Moves On This Week's Billboard 200|last=McIntyre|first=Hugh|website=[[Forbes]]|date=16 August 2019|accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nCredits adapted from the album liner notes.<ref name=\"Notes\">{{cite AV media notes|year=2019|title=High Expectations|others=Mabel|publisher=[[Polydor Records]]|id=B0030376}}</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| total_length = 41:41\n| title1 = High Expectations (Intro)\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Mabel (singer)|Mabel McVey]]|[[Tre Jean-Marie]]|[[Joel Compass]]}}\n| extra1 = {{hlist|Jean-Marie}}\n| length1 = 3:27\n| title2 = Bad Behaviour\n| writer2 = {{hlist|McVey|[[Marlon Roudette]]|[[Dre Skull|Andrew Hershey]]}}\n| extra2 = {{hlist|Dre Skull|[[Wildlife!|WILDLIFE!]]{{ref|a|[a]}}|Cameron Gower Poole{{ref|b|[b]}}}}\n| length2 = 3:25\n| title3 = [[Don't Call Me Up]]\n| writer3 = {{hlist|McVey|[[Camille Purcell|Kamille]]|[[Steve Mac|Mac]]}}\n| extra3 = Steve Mac\n| length3 = 2:58\n| title4 = FML\n| writer4 = {{hlist|McVey|[[Oak Felder|Warren Okay Felder]]|Roudette|[[Sarah Aarons]]|Kelly Kiara